{"actual_usd":0.159235,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":399,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30650,"reply":"\"I can see why that sounds like a word game at first.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and glance up at the clear morning sky beyond the square, taking a second to answer carefully.* \"Christians aren’t saying God is three beings who cooperate nicely. We’re saying God is one in being, and three in person — Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.\"\n\n*I shift my weight a little on the bench.* \"Now, I know that can sound like ducking the question, but it’s trying to protect two things Scripture says at once: there is only one God, and yet the Father is God, the Son is God, and the Spirit is God — and they are not each other.\"\n\n\"It’s not three gods because Christians do not divide God’s being into three separate divine centers the way you’d have three men, three angels, or three anything else created.\" *I tap the page lightly.* \"It’s one divine life, one divine essence, one Lord. The threeness is personal, not numerical in the sense of counting separate gods.\"\n\n*I give a small, apologetic half-smile.* \"To be plain: the Trinity is not easy because God is not a larger version of the kinds of things we’re used to counting. If I say three people, you picture three beings. Fair enough. But in Christian teaching, the three Persons are not three beings. That’s exactly where the mystery sits.\"\n\n\"Deuteronomy says, ‘The Lord our God is one Lord.’ And then in the New Testament, Jesus speaks to the Father, sends the Spirit, and yet receives the honor due to God.\" *I spread one hand a little.* \"So the church didn’t invent the tension. She was trying not to lie about what had been revealed.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can give you the cleanest short version of the logic Christians are trying to hold — without the church-history furniture.\"","rolling_24h_usd":41.40144500000004,"run_id":"0f933766-0605-44e8-9a10-1db98aad0b3f"}
